WEBVTT

00:06.000 --> 00:12.074
Advertise your product or brand here
contact www.OpenSubtitles.org today

00:26.280 --> 00:27.930
(CLASSICAL MUSIC PLAYING)

00:44.920 --> 00:49.926
What separates the casual Jane
Austen fan from the aficionado?

00:50.640 --> 00:55.806
Is it her admiration for the style
and manners of the Regency era?

00:56.480 --> 00:59.848
The number of times
she has read Austen's novels?

01:00.080 --> 01:03.687
Or her consuming love
for Mr. Darcy?

01:09.160 --> 01:12.050
<i>♪ L-O-V-E-D-A-R-C-Y</i>

01:13.600 --> 01:14.647
Nice cup.

01:14.800 --> 01:15.847
Thanks.

01:17.040 --> 01:19.930
<i>♪ And it begins like any other</i>

01:20.600 --> 01:22.443
<i>♪ Since she was very young</i>

01:23.000 --> 01:24.331
Oh.

01:24.400 --> 01:26.164
Sexy.

01:26.320 --> 01:27.606
Okay.

01:27.680 --> 01:28.886
I'll see you for lunch.

01:29.000 --> 01:30.240
Yeah, okay.

01:36.080 --> 01:38.367
<i>♪ You try to catch her eye</i>

01:40.120 --> 01:42.361
<i>♪ But she doesn't want to see</i>

01:45.480 --> 01:46.845
<i>MAN: (ON TV)
Miss Bennet...</i>

01:48.200 --> 01:50.168
This is the best part.

01:50.400 --> 01:54.166
<i>♪ She's singing
my boy loves me</i>

01:54.240 --> 01:56.049
Unbelievable.

01:58.720 --> 02:03.806
<i>♪ My boy loves me I know ♪</i>

02:11.200 --> 02:12.565
Hey, Jane.
Ex-boyfriend alert.

02:12.680 --> 02:15.081
Hey, Horseface.

02:15.280 --> 02:16.486
Jimmy, what are you doing here?

02:16.560 --> 02:18.289
Well, I heard you
broke up with Greg.

02:18.400 --> 02:21.882
So that means you're free
to go bowling tonight.

02:22.040 --> 02:23.610
Oops!
Jimmy! You know what?

02:23.760 --> 02:26.240
If "no" was
unclear last time...

02:27.680 --> 02:29.011
I don't wanna see you again.

02:31.160 --> 02:35.165
I picked you on purpose, Jane Hayes.
Thirty plus, clock ticking.

02:35.280 --> 02:37.408
I'm as good as it gets, baby.

02:37.600 --> 02:40.763
<i>MRS. WATTLESBROOK: A true aficionado
of Austen does so much more</i>

02:40.840 --> 02:43.844
<i>than merely read her novels and
admire her world from afar.</i>

02:44.360 --> 02:45.600
Excuse me.

02:46.040 --> 02:48.407
She finds her way here

02:49.360 --> 02:54.685
to the world's only immersive
Austen experience.

02:56.360 --> 02:57.600
MOLLY:
Is that a Chihuahua?

02:58.000 --> 02:59.684
It's a lamb. Shut up.
Just trying to hear it.

02:59.800 --> 03:00.926
This looks really cheap.

03:01.000 --> 03:03.002
AGENT: I've toured the grounds
and it's not cheap.

03:03.200 --> 03:06.488
This is high class.
This is big time.

03:06.600 --> 03:09.206
Jane, are you really
gonna blow your entire

03:09.320 --> 03:11.846
life savings on
an "Austen experience"?

03:12.280 --> 03:13.770
Now, hold on just a second,

03:13.880 --> 03:15.006
here at Sensuous Travel,

03:15.120 --> 03:17.248
we are not just another
run-of-the-mill vacation place.

03:17.360 --> 03:20.887
This is what we call
an "LC." A Life-Changer.

03:21.080 --> 03:25.244
You get to play the heroine of
your very own Jane Austen story.

03:25.600 --> 03:27.125
Would you like to
see some of the staff?

03:27.360 --> 03:28.964
Yeah.
No.

03:29.400 --> 03:32.006
Now this is Barnaby.
He's a vegan.

03:32.080 --> 03:34.082
He enjoys nightly
dips in the pond,

03:34.200 --> 03:36.202
and he has a pony
named Sparkles Pancake.

03:36.280 --> 03:37.770
That is horrendous.

03:37.920 --> 03:40.446
I also heard that people in those
days didn't wear underwear.

03:40.520 --> 03:41.567
That's a lie.

03:41.640 --> 03:42.641
It's not a lie.

03:43.200 --> 03:47.250
Look, every stay at Austenland
ends with a real live ball,

03:47.440 --> 03:50.728
as in ballroom,
as in happily ever after.

03:51.120 --> 03:52.167
Do you understand
what I'm saying?

03:52.320 --> 03:53.321
Totally.

03:53.440 --> 03:58.002
Jane. So you go on some fancy vacation,
then what do you come home to?

03:58.120 --> 04:00.248
Nothing except for
an empty bank account.

04:00.440 --> 04:04.081
Why don't you save up
for a real life-changer?

04:05.200 --> 04:07.043
Like what?
Well, like...

04:07.200 --> 04:09.726
That's fine. Maybe come back
another time without your friend.

04:09.840 --> 04:10.921
We'll get you squared away.

04:11.000 --> 04:13.162
I think I can figure out some
kind of layaway program for you.

04:14.160 --> 04:15.525
Thank you so much.

04:15.680 --> 04:18.923
You guys take care. Thanks for being you.
Appreciate you.

04:25.960 --> 04:30.682
Listen, this is my one chance to
really live in Austen's world. Okay?

04:30.840 --> 04:32.285
I'm her biggest fan.

04:32.480 --> 04:33.527
Come on.

04:33.680 --> 04:34.727
No. No.

04:35.000 --> 04:36.604
You used to be a fan.

04:36.840 --> 04:38.490
You are an addict.

04:38.880 --> 04:41.087
You don't have to go in there because
I'm packing. It's a mess in there.

04:41.200 --> 04:42.531
You don't wanna go in there.

04:42.680 --> 04:46.207
Oh, Janey.
It's gotten so much worse.

04:49.640 --> 04:50.721
(SQUEAKING)
I love you.

04:50.840 --> 04:52.524
It's a collector's item
and that's why I have it.

04:52.600 --> 04:53.726
<i>I have 10,000 a year.</i>

04:54.640 --> 04:56.051
I've changed my mind.

04:56.200 --> 04:58.965
I totally support you
going to this place,

04:59.160 --> 05:01.401
because I'm sure
that the fantasy

05:01.560 --> 05:03.767
will not be as
fulfilling as you imagine.

05:03.920 --> 05:05.331
I don't think you
know where I'm going.

05:05.400 --> 05:08.370
We could make a wager on it.
Fine.

05:08.480 --> 05:12.690
If I win,
you de-Austen your room.

05:15.080 --> 05:17.082
Okay.
Fine.

05:17.400 --> 05:21.405
And if you really must go, I
made you a little farewell gift.

05:21.520 --> 05:23.090
You did?

05:24.080 --> 05:25.411
Aw.

05:27.680 --> 05:28.841
Wow.

05:29.760 --> 05:32.331
Which historical era
is this supposed to be from?

05:32.400 --> 05:34.687
Hey, I spent three
days working on it.

05:34.800 --> 05:36.609
Come here, let's hug it out.

05:37.920 --> 05:39.285
Thank you.
Okay.

05:39.400 --> 05:43.928
When you get back, just clear
this crap out because it's weird.

05:44.080 --> 05:45.525
It's a hobby.
It's really weird.

05:45.800 --> 05:49.088
<i>♪ Ooh, baby, do you know
what that's worth?</i>

05:49.360 --> 05:53.160
<i>♪ Ooh, heaven is
a place on earth</i>

05:53.240 --> 05:57.040
<i>♪ They say in heaven
love comes first</i>

05:57.400 --> 06:00.927
<i>♪ We'll make heaven
a place on earth</i>

06:01.280 --> 06:05.444
<i>♪ Ooh, heaven is
a place on earth</i>

06:22.280 --> 06:25.489
<i>♪ When the night falls down ♪</i>

06:25.880 --> 06:26.927
Oh!

06:27.000 --> 06:28.809
Do you need a hand?

06:30.480 --> 06:32.687
Yay, an American.

06:33.000 --> 06:36.163
I can't understand what the natives say.
(CHUCKLES)

06:36.800 --> 06:39.087
I think this is where we're
supposed to wait, right?

06:39.160 --> 06:40.241
You're going to
the Darcy place, too?

06:40.320 --> 06:41.401
Yes.

06:41.520 --> 06:43.090
I memorized
the first three chapters

06:43.160 --> 06:44.571
<i>of Pride and Prejudice
when I was 13.</i>

06:44.920 --> 06:47.002
(CHUCKLES)
What's that?

06:47.160 --> 06:48.650
Oh. Um...

06:50.000 --> 06:52.128
So why are you
going to this place?

06:52.360 --> 06:55.921
Because I'm gonna look great
in those wench gowns.

06:56.840 --> 07:00.845
Ooh. Gosh, I hope they
give me a cape, too.

07:00.960 --> 07:02.928
Were we not supposed
to come in costume?

07:03.040 --> 07:05.247
Thank goodness
you're coming and not her.

07:05.840 --> 07:08.047
I'm Jane, by the way.

07:08.160 --> 07:11.801
Oh, goody.
Introductions. Look.

07:13.520 --> 07:14.601
Hi.

07:15.040 --> 07:18.840
I'm Miss Elizabeth Charming.

07:19.240 --> 07:22.323
It's a pretty name, isn't it?
I requested it.

07:22.440 --> 07:25.364
Yes, it's very beautiful.
I can't wait to pick a name.

07:26.120 --> 07:28.487
How about Miss Pepperpot?

07:28.600 --> 07:30.887
Or Miss Wiggly Wiggins?

07:31.040 --> 07:33.247
Those are nice.
(CAR HONKING)

07:36.240 --> 07:39.244
I knew this place
would be magical.

07:39.360 --> 07:42.330
They even got us
a car from the 1800s.

07:44.000 --> 07:48.528
Oh, thank you so much.
I'm Miss Charming.

07:49.360 --> 07:50.930
This way.

07:51.040 --> 07:52.724
MAN:
Bloody Americans!

07:52.880 --> 07:54.370
Mind the gap.

07:56.400 --> 07:59.688
Sorry. I was told I was
supposed to wear a costume.

07:59.760 --> 08:01.410
So was I.

08:09.960 --> 08:12.327
God save the Queen!

08:16.280 --> 08:19.443
MISS CHARMING: Hey, do you think this
is the <i>Chitty Chitty Bang Bang</i> car?

08:30.200 --> 08:31.611
(HONKING)

08:36.760 --> 08:39.001
It's smaller than I expected.

08:39.200 --> 08:41.679
Welcome to the Regency era.

08:41.799 --> 08:43.450
This is just a stop before
we go to the big house.

08:43.559 --> 08:44.971
I am Mrs. Wattlesbrook.
Okay.

08:45.080 --> 08:48.801
Miss Charming, I hope your
travel was endurable.

08:48.920 --> 08:50.604
Oh, yes!

08:52.160 --> 08:54.481
(CLEARS THROAT) Jane Hayes.
Yes.

08:54.640 --> 08:57.450
And I've been thinking
about my pseudonym,

08:57.640 --> 09:00.450
and I was thinking
Miss Joyful, maybe?

09:00.560 --> 09:03.928
Oh, yes. You've already
been assigned a name.

09:04.000 --> 09:05.365
Miss Erstwhile.

09:05.800 --> 09:07.006
Miss Erstwhile?

09:07.120 --> 09:09.361
Martin.
Take their luggage in.

09:09.480 --> 09:11.926
And get the carriage ready
to take us up to the manor.

09:15.160 --> 09:17.288
Martin.
Ma'am.

09:18.640 --> 09:20.369
Good luck.
Thanks.

09:20.480 --> 09:23.689
Complete immersion
in the Regency era

09:23.760 --> 09:26.969
is the only way to truly
appreciate Austen's England.

09:27.080 --> 09:28.320
Wouldn't you say so,
Miss Charming?

09:28.800 --> 09:30.609
(IN BRITISH ACCENT)
Righto!

09:31.040 --> 09:32.929
Just to avoid any confusion,

09:33.000 --> 09:37.164
I'd like you to know that we do
offer several distinct experiences.

09:37.680 --> 09:40.684
You have paid for
the Basic Copper package,

09:41.240 --> 09:43.720
while the other
ladies in the party

09:43.840 --> 09:46.320
are part of
the Platinum Elite package.

09:46.600 --> 09:48.090
Oh. Okay.

09:48.160 --> 09:50.481
I'm sure you'll understand there will
be some exclusions to your trip.

09:50.600 --> 09:54.047
I mean, I'm just so
excited to be here,

09:54.120 --> 09:56.282
and I've dreamed
about this for so long.

09:56.360 --> 09:58.328
All of my guests
will experience

09:58.400 --> 10:00.528
romance with one of our actors.

10:00.600 --> 10:03.683
But I must emphasize
there is to be no touching

10:04.280 --> 10:07.887
other than the necessary social graces.
Not a chance.

10:08.080 --> 10:09.969
I also expect
all my guests to maintain

10:10.080 --> 10:12.003
appropriate manners
and conversation

10:12.120 --> 10:14.487
and to eschew
all things modern.

10:14.640 --> 10:16.290
Any flagrant
disobedience will result

10:16.360 --> 10:17.930
in the early
termination of your stay.

10:18.520 --> 10:19.806
You don't have
to worry about me.

10:19.880 --> 10:22.201
I know Austen's
books intimately.

10:27.320 --> 10:31.166
A big fire for
a hot summer's day.

10:35.120 --> 10:36.326
(LAUGHING)

10:37.760 --> 10:40.730
We need to push up
the sisters. There we go.

10:42.240 --> 10:44.083
That's as far as I can go.

10:44.720 --> 10:46.404
It's looking good.

10:50.680 --> 10:53.411
<i>♪ Has it been a day or a week</i>

10:53.480 --> 10:55.926
<i>♪ As my eyes begin to close</i>

10:56.200 --> 10:59.329
So we have this absolutely
delightful chiffon piece.

10:59.400 --> 11:01.402
And I don't know
how you feel about lavender.

11:01.480 --> 11:02.766
I call it lilac.

11:02.920 --> 11:04.160
"Lilac."

11:04.240 --> 11:06.925
This I do think is very
magnificent and elegant.

11:07.080 --> 11:08.445
Salmon!

11:08.600 --> 11:09.965
Salmon. Absolutely.

11:10.960 --> 11:14.931
<i>♪ These dreams under my pillow</i>

11:15.240 --> 11:17.004
Kinda washes you out.

11:18.040 --> 11:20.327
<i>♪ Of these white nights ♪</i>

11:20.560 --> 11:23.848
Look how skinny I look
with my hand behind my back.

11:26.760 --> 11:28.046
Let's go meet the men.

11:28.160 --> 11:29.446
Okay.

11:32.000 --> 11:33.365
(SIGHS)

11:41.800 --> 11:44.121
I'm so sorry,
my dear, but I'm afraid

11:44.240 --> 11:46.527
this carriage only
takes two passengers.

11:47.960 --> 11:49.041
Okay.

11:49.160 --> 11:50.286
Sorry.

11:50.440 --> 11:54.047
Hey, do you think we'll be
robbed by some highwaymen?

13:04.640 --> 13:06.768
MRS. WATTLESBROOK: Martin,
hurry up with those bags.

13:06.840 --> 13:08.968
My God, look at those.

13:10.080 --> 13:13.163
Hallelujah. Oh!

13:13.680 --> 13:14.761
(CLEARS THROAT)

13:17.120 --> 13:20.488
Do you think those
are their real faces?

13:22.120 --> 13:26.330
And for you, Miss Charming, we have
our finest Platinum level room.

13:30.400 --> 13:31.561
Oh!

13:35.160 --> 13:37.367
How old-fashioned.

13:38.280 --> 13:40.726
Miss Erstwhile.
If you follow me.

13:44.560 --> 13:47.689
Hey! It's bloody brilliant!

13:47.920 --> 13:50.082
MRS. WATTLESBROOK:
Where are you? We can't dilly-dally.

13:53.000 --> 13:56.527
And you, of course, have one of
our loveliest Copper level rooms.

14:01.280 --> 14:02.884
We meet for dinner at 8:00.

14:02.960 --> 14:05.201
I expect you can find your
own way to the drawing room.

14:05.440 --> 14:07.886
I wouldn't miss
it for the world.

14:36.120 --> 14:38.771
With me? Yes.

14:45.000 --> 14:46.161
MISS CHARMING: Jane!

14:46.800 --> 14:51.408
Jane? Come here.
All the statues look at you!

14:51.800 --> 14:53.325
(DOOR OPENING)

14:59.880 --> 15:03.771
Look. It's one of
those Mr. Darcy guys.

15:04.480 --> 15:08.007
May I present Miss
Elizabeth Charming.

15:08.160 --> 15:10.481
Heiress to the vast
Charming fortune.

15:10.640 --> 15:14.008
(IN BRITISH ACCENT)
Top of the evening to you.

15:15.080 --> 15:17.048
And Miss Jane Erstwhile.

15:17.200 --> 15:20.090
An orphan of no fortune,
who we've taken in

15:20.160 --> 15:22.049
out of the goodness
of our hearts.

15:23.000 --> 15:26.800
Colonel Andrews, the second
son of the Earl of Denton.

15:27.880 --> 15:30.884
I have never before
beheld such beauty...

15:33.200 --> 15:34.690
And class.

15:35.840 --> 15:38.730
What a very pleasant
pleasure it is indeed.

15:39.840 --> 15:42.684
And my dear nephew,
Henry Nobley.

15:42.840 --> 15:43.921
(CLEARS THROAT)

15:44.480 --> 15:47.131
Goody.
There's one for each of us.

15:48.920 --> 15:54.006
And, of course, our honored
guest, Lady Amelia Heartwright.

15:55.880 --> 15:58.087
MISS CHARMING:
What the H?

15:59.800 --> 16:04.931
I've been so lonely here without
other young women to entertain me.

16:05.160 --> 16:08.050
All day, stuck with these men.

16:09.400 --> 16:11.687
And that is my husband.

16:11.760 --> 16:12.807
(BURPS)

16:12.880 --> 16:14.962
Do sit down.

16:18.520 --> 16:21.126
I do hope it will not
rain on us tomorrow.

16:21.240 --> 16:25.564
It would be so lovely to take
a turn around the gardens.

16:27.840 --> 16:30.810
I sure would like you

16:31.000 --> 16:35.289
to turn me upside
down in the garden.

16:35.600 --> 16:36.806
Pardon me?

16:37.000 --> 16:40.209
I think Miss Charming just
means she loves the outdoors.

16:40.400 --> 16:41.367
Right.

16:41.440 --> 16:42.521
Bless.

16:43.760 --> 16:46.240
Do you see something in my eye?

16:46.440 --> 16:49.922
I'm afraid I can't
see in this low light.

16:50.480 --> 16:51.606
(MISS CHARMING LAUGHING)

16:51.920 --> 16:55.447
Oh, Mr. Nobley.

16:55.680 --> 16:58.286
You really are quite a bloke.

16:58.440 --> 17:02.525
It would appear to be my duty
to gaze into your eyes.

17:02.720 --> 17:04.801
I'm a military man,
I'd never shirk my duty.

17:05.079 --> 17:07.208
Allow me, Miss Charming.

17:09.480 --> 17:13.007
Yes. Yes, there is
something there. Fire.

17:13.440 --> 17:17.525
I say, Miss Charming, you certainly
do live up to your name.

17:17.720 --> 17:19.050
(BELL TINKLING)

17:19.119 --> 17:20.804
Tally-ho!

17:21.960 --> 17:24.611
MRS. WATTLESBROOK: I do hope
you all enjoy the food.

17:31.560 --> 17:33.130
AMELIA: Have you lost
your appetite, Mr. Nobley?

17:33.280 --> 17:34.850
Somewhat.

17:35.280 --> 17:37.123
Something on your mind?

17:37.280 --> 17:39.647
Absolutely nothing's
on my mind, thank you.

17:39.760 --> 17:42.684
Prudence, a little bit more of the
peacock paté, when you're ready.

17:47.560 --> 17:48.766
(BELL TINKLING)

17:48.840 --> 17:50.330
I can't believe
I'm really here.

17:52.400 --> 17:53.811
Jane.
Yeah?

17:53.880 --> 17:56.929
Why don't you try out
some of that fancy talk?

17:58.320 --> 18:01.767
Mr. Nobley, I hear there is
a ball on our last night.

18:01.840 --> 18:02.966
Do you enjoy dancing?

18:03.080 --> 18:04.161
Not particularly.

18:04.560 --> 18:06.847
AMELIA: (CHUCKLES)
Scandalous.

18:07.000 --> 18:11.164
I am sure you have escorted many a
fine lady on to the dance floor.

18:11.680 --> 18:14.126
ANDREWS: I would say
that manners maketh man.

18:14.200 --> 18:16.965
I look forward to having the
pleasure of standing opposite you.

18:17.080 --> 18:20.607
But dancing is the true hallmark...
You do?

18:20.720 --> 18:22.802
...of a <i>gentilhomme d'honneur.</i>

18:22.920 --> 18:24.968
MR. WATTLESBROOK: Pass the
sheep's eyeballs, will you?

18:25.200 --> 18:28.602
Traditionally, dancing
is a match-making custom.

18:28.680 --> 18:29.727
Oh, yes.

18:29.800 --> 18:32.201
However, it fails
unless both partners

18:32.320 --> 18:34.641
are equally fond of each other.

18:34.840 --> 18:37.411
You could say the same
about any social intercourse.

18:37.520 --> 18:38.885
Intercourse?

18:39.520 --> 18:42.524
Such as talking to someone
or having dinner with them.

18:42.680 --> 18:47.049
Society demands that we engage in a social
intercourse in order to seem courteous.

18:47.200 --> 18:52.525
Yet, in most cases, such
actions are ultimately vulgar.

18:52.760 --> 18:54.728
I really adore conversating.

18:54.880 --> 18:56.291
(ALL CHUCKLING)

18:56.800 --> 18:58.484
Do you really believe,
Mr. Nobley,

18:58.560 --> 19:01.484
that you can know the worth
of a person at a glance?

19:01.760 --> 19:03.649
Can you tell me that
within the first few moments

19:03.720 --> 19:06.166
of meeting each
person in this room,

19:06.400 --> 19:10.086
you didn't form firm opinions
of their character?

19:11.680 --> 19:15.651
Well, it would be a shame if my first
impression of you proved correct.

19:16.000 --> 19:19.925
Well, Miss Erstwhile, I for one
am so pleased you are here.

19:20.120 --> 19:24.728
Another woman who understands,
as I do, the rocky road of love.

19:25.520 --> 19:29.684
Mrs. Wattlesbrook told me
of your tragic story.

19:30.800 --> 19:31.926
What?

19:32.040 --> 19:34.407
I try to learn a great
deal about my clients

19:34.520 --> 19:36.841
so that I can better
prepare for their stay.

19:37.600 --> 19:42.686
You have been unlucky
in love, shall we say?

19:43.600 --> 19:45.489
AMELIA: We most definitely
should say.

19:46.000 --> 19:50.562
At your age,
with no husband, no kinder...

19:52.560 --> 19:53.561
I'm sorry.

19:53.640 --> 19:56.723
The clock is ticking. Tick-took,
tick-took. Oh, bugger.

19:57.440 --> 19:58.930
ANDREWS:
How unfortunate.

20:01.160 --> 20:02.650
Excuse me.

20:02.840 --> 20:04.330
Good duck.

20:06.800 --> 20:11.249
Jane. Jane! Jane.
Oh, I'm so sorry.

20:11.520 --> 20:15.002
You know, I know how it feels to
be treated badly by stupid men.

20:15.200 --> 20:16.565
I really do.

20:16.680 --> 20:18.569
Jane, come on.
Give me a hug.

20:20.080 --> 20:22.731
Come on. At least it's not
gonna happen at this place.

20:23.080 --> 20:25.321
Besides, you'll feel
totally different tomorrow.

20:26.080 --> 20:28.845
Think about all the people in
the world that hang themselves.

20:30.040 --> 20:32.566
And then the next day,
they feel different,

20:32.680 --> 20:35.251
but there's nothing
they can do about it.

20:35.520 --> 20:37.727
Don't hang yourself, Jane.
Mmm-hmm.

20:38.200 --> 20:42.171
Anyway, if you need anything,
just call me. I'm right down the hall.

20:42.440 --> 20:45.762
Well, actually,
I'm not right down the hall

20:46.480 --> 20:50.326
because you're in the servants' wing.
You're in the creepy tower.

20:51.520 --> 20:54.967
God, sometimes I think
about you here at night.

20:56.160 --> 20:57.969
Must be really scary.

20:58.760 --> 21:00.524
It's okay.
Anyway.

21:01.520 --> 21:03.966
And, Jane,
the maid told me that...

21:04.080 --> 21:07.607
FYI, she said don't
use the chamber pots.

21:08.320 --> 21:11.688
Apparently the toilets
really do flush here,

21:12.320 --> 21:16.120
and they don't know what to do
if it's just piled high.

21:17.920 --> 21:19.046
Right.

21:24.920 --> 21:26.922
Of course,
he made all his money

21:27.040 --> 21:29.042
selling quicklime
on the continent.

21:29.120 --> 21:32.920
You can never have enough whitewash,
as my grandfather used to say.

21:33.800 --> 21:36.451
Then he contracted
dysentery and died.

21:36.800 --> 21:38.404
Tap-tap.

21:39.560 --> 21:42.450
Good morrow, sir.
'Tis I.

21:43.200 --> 21:44.964
Shall we promenade?
(SIGHS)

21:48.480 --> 21:52.121
Oh. Oh, I say.
Miss Erstwhile, do join us.

21:52.480 --> 21:54.084
Yes, make haste.

21:54.920 --> 21:57.810
I think I'll go
find some shade.

21:58.400 --> 22:01.244
Really? How peculiar.

22:01.880 --> 22:03.120
She's been too much in the sun.
Come, sir.

22:07.280 --> 22:09.169
<i>MRS. WATTLESBROOK: (ON PA)
Your hunting excursion is commencing</i>

22:09.240 --> 22:11.049
<i>on the upper
paddock at the stable</i>

22:11.200 --> 22:13.703
<i>where you will be assigned
an appropriate mount.</i>

22:13.729 --> 22:15.886
(GASPS)
(CHICKENS CLUCKING)

22:15.960 --> 22:17.200
MARTIN: Sorry.

22:17.680 --> 22:20.686
Sorry.
I'm not spying on you.

22:20.760 --> 22:23.604
I'm afraid you caught me
at an unladylike moment.

22:23.840 --> 22:27.003
Mrs. Wattlesbrook will probably
rap my knuckles or something.

22:27.160 --> 22:28.924
Tell me about it.

22:29.080 --> 22:33.210
So you hail from
the former colonies?

22:33.280 --> 22:34.770
(LAUGHS)

22:35.120 --> 22:39.409
I'm sorry, that's pretty bad. I'm not
really here to do the "ye olde" stuff.

22:41.240 --> 22:44.801
I'm probably not supposed to be
talking to the servants anyway.

22:45.280 --> 22:49.968
I thought I'd come here and be a total
pro at this, but I don't know...

22:50.120 --> 22:52.248
Yeah. Maybe you need
a coach or something.

22:53.280 --> 22:56.443
Yeah. I'm definitely not
supposed to talk to you.

22:57.720 --> 22:59.245
And yet,

23:00.800 --> 23:02.404
here you are.

23:02.480 --> 23:04.448
(ANDREWS SPEAKING INDISTINCTLY)

23:04.520 --> 23:06.090
That's... I have to...

23:06.200 --> 23:10.008
ANDREWS: Where are you?
Miss Erstwhile, there you are.

23:10.120 --> 23:11.804
Yes, hello. I... I was
just saying to Nobley here

23:12.240 --> 23:14.368
our divine Miss Erstwhile
seems to have escaped us.

23:14.480 --> 23:15.845
And let us not see if
we cannot find her out...

23:15.960 --> 23:19.806
I was hot so I stopped in here,
you know, and then I sat...

23:20.000 --> 23:23.641
I say, Miss Erstwhile,
you are tongue-tied today.

23:23.720 --> 23:26.405
What sordid secrets is your
mouth trying to hide from us?

23:26.600 --> 23:28.170
No, no secrets. No.
Do tell me at once.

23:28.360 --> 23:29.407
I simply must know.
Andrews!

23:32.120 --> 23:33.326
Can't you see
that she's unwell?

23:33.480 --> 23:34.686
No, I'm fine.
Thank you...

23:34.840 --> 23:37.002
Unwell? Perhaps you have a
touch of the vapors? Or mange?

23:37.120 --> 23:38.770
Either way,
bell jar on the tummy.

23:38.880 --> 23:40.530
Sucks out all
the vicious vapors.

23:40.640 --> 23:42.608
And leeches on the ankles...
Andrews, shut up.

23:42.960 --> 23:43.961
What?

23:44.640 --> 23:46.051
(MISS CHARMING HOOTING)

23:46.120 --> 23:49.920
Hi. Ladies and gents,
please take notice!

23:50.160 --> 23:51.969
I've just got the schedule,

23:52.080 --> 23:55.004
and look, it says we get
to go hunting on horseback.

23:55.320 --> 23:59.530
Can you believe it?
Real horses and real guns!

24:00.320 --> 24:01.685
Release the hounds!

24:01.760 --> 24:04.570
Tally-ho.
A-hunting we will go.

24:04.880 --> 24:07.611
The British are coming.
The British are coming!

24:07.840 --> 24:09.569
Shall we go?
Shall we?

24:09.720 --> 24:13.805
Hey, stable boy.
You're way too slow! Come on!

24:19.640 --> 24:22.041
I've never shot
a hunting rifle before.

24:22.480 --> 24:25.404
ANDREWS: Now, the whole thing with the
gun, darling, is that you have to cock it.

24:25.480 --> 24:27.642
Just hold the barrel. There.

24:28.000 --> 24:30.810
And then gently
pull the trigger.

24:32.080 --> 24:33.650
MR. NOBLEY: Have you ever
fired a loaded weapon before?

24:33.760 --> 24:36.889
Actually, I think you might
be quite impressed by my...

24:37.040 --> 24:38.166
Big cock.
...skills.

24:38.240 --> 24:40.049
I will be.
(EXCLAIMS) Ow!

24:40.520 --> 24:42.045
Just a little closer there.

24:42.160 --> 24:43.650
JANE: Yeah,
I think I get the basics.

24:46.560 --> 24:47.721
Ready, ladies?

24:49.000 --> 24:52.925
Face down range.
Load. And make ready.

24:53.360 --> 24:54.407
And, pull!

24:58.480 --> 25:00.721
Fly in my eye.

25:10.360 --> 25:14.922
My... Miss Erstwhile. What a
talented little nut you are.

25:15.080 --> 25:16.081
JANE: Yeah.

25:16.200 --> 25:18.487
I guess I get the basics of it.

25:18.760 --> 25:21.491
I didn't think we were really
supposed to kill them.

25:21.600 --> 25:23.443
What are we supposed
to eat for dinner?

25:24.440 --> 25:27.284
Anyone for pheasant? Me.
(CHUCKLING)

25:31.360 --> 25:33.931
ANDREWS: Of course, all these
horses are thoroughbreds.

25:34.560 --> 25:39.043
They come from the local stud.
Well, I'm too busy, you see.

25:39.760 --> 25:42.081
There's something
wrong with the horse.

25:42.400 --> 25:44.846
Crap Copper package.

25:47.120 --> 25:50.408
MARTIN: Little bit tight. Have
to give you a rub down tonight.

25:51.120 --> 25:52.246
Excuse me?

25:52.360 --> 25:53.691
The horse.

25:53.800 --> 25:55.131
(CHUCKLES)
Right, sorry.

25:58.480 --> 26:00.130
There we go.
Oh!

26:01.240 --> 26:02.241
Thank you.

26:03.720 --> 26:05.324
I'll be back in
a crack with a new horse.

26:05.440 --> 26:07.044
Okay.

26:13.360 --> 26:16.330
<i>♪ Somewhere there's
a book of me</i>

26:17.720 --> 26:20.371
<i>♪ Waiting for someone to read it</i>

26:22.000 --> 26:23.843
<i>♪ And I really believe it</i>

26:23.920 --> 26:25.331
(THUNDER RUMBLING)

26:25.400 --> 26:27.801
<i>♪ Just wish that
I could see it</i>

26:29.840 --> 26:33.162
<i>♪ And I keep losing track
of where I'm meant to be</i>

26:34.960 --> 26:38.123
<i>♪ If you know it you would be there</i>
(THUNDER RUMBLING)

26:38.720 --> 26:41.530
<i>♪ 'Cause I know
that you're a good man</i>

26:42.600 --> 26:44.887
<i>♪ But you like
to keep that secret ♪</i>

26:45.200 --> 26:47.487
Oh. Hi.

26:49.520 --> 26:50.931
Did that stable
boy abandon you?

26:51.040 --> 26:52.451
No, he's coming right back.

26:55.360 --> 26:58.648
Well, I wasn't raised to leave
a woman alone in the woods.

26:58.920 --> 27:01.207
I'm really... I'm fine.
(THUNDER CRASHING)

27:01.880 --> 27:03.689
Well, there's...

27:03.800 --> 27:04.961
All right, come on.
Get up.

27:05.080 --> 27:06.206
Both of us on the one horse?

27:06.280 --> 27:09.011
I don't know if that's gonna
really work for me...

27:09.080 --> 27:11.392
Right, are you ready?
One, two, three.

27:11.418 --> 27:11.995
No, no.

27:12.280 --> 27:13.611
(EXCLAIMS)

27:14.040 --> 27:15.530
Okay.

27:15.960 --> 27:18.930
We're not gonna be able to outrun the
storm unless you straddle the horse.

27:19.040 --> 27:22.044
Straddle... Not possible
in this rig. Sorry.

27:24.200 --> 27:25.565
Whoa, whoa, whoa!

27:27.760 --> 27:31.606
Get forward. Forward. That's it, more.
Forward? Okay. Well...

27:32.680 --> 27:33.806
Take the reins.

27:36.320 --> 27:42.487
Now, anyone who can shoot a gun
like that can ride a horse.

27:42.680 --> 27:43.920
Come on.

27:44.080 --> 27:45.605
Do you have me?

27:45.760 --> 27:48.650
I've got you fine.
Thank you.

28:00.640 --> 28:01.687
Jane.

28:06.800 --> 28:07.801
Come here.

28:07.920 --> 28:08.967
I know,
but it's a little hard...

28:09.080 --> 28:11.606
No, your leg, your leg. No.
Yeah, okay.

28:12.560 --> 28:13.686
JANE: Thank you.

28:13.800 --> 28:15.006
Jane.

28:15.280 --> 28:18.170
What the hell do you think you were
doing leaving her alone like that?

28:18.920 --> 28:20.126
I'm sorry, I was coming.

28:20.200 --> 28:23.443
No, I was fine,
actually, Mr. Nobley.

28:23.960 --> 28:27.965
There you are, Mr. Nobley. I was about
to arouse a search party. (GASPS)

28:29.000 --> 28:32.891
Miss Erstwhile. What ghastly
thing happened to you?

28:33.520 --> 28:37.844
I think I'm just
gonna go powder my nose.

28:43.320 --> 28:45.482
<i>MRS. WATTLESBROOK: Everyone, please
assemble in the drawing room</i>

28:45.560 --> 28:47.210
<i>for this evening's whist drive.</i>

28:47.760 --> 28:52.368
<i>Partners will be assigned according
to ability and package status.</i>

28:54.400 --> 28:56.721
MRS. WATTLESBROOK: I do believe
I start this one, do I not?

28:56.800 --> 28:57.961
AMELIA: I'm just
so happy. I...

28:58.040 --> 29:00.008
See if you can beat that.

29:00.200 --> 29:02.168
ANDREWS: Well,
there's a card.

29:04.560 --> 29:07.848
A proper lady does not doodle the
evening away, Miss Erstwhile.

29:11.600 --> 29:13.682
You're looking well,
Mr. Nobley.

29:13.840 --> 29:15.569
The rain refreshed
your spirits, did it?

29:17.320 --> 29:18.651
Hardly.

29:20.000 --> 29:21.161
(CHUCKLES)

29:21.360 --> 29:23.727
I say, who needs
the outdoors when

29:23.800 --> 29:26.690
you ladies are such
a breath of fresh air?

29:27.000 --> 29:28.081
(ALL CHUCKLING)

29:28.200 --> 29:31.409
Colonel, you really
are a saucy monkey.

29:32.360 --> 29:36.922
Miss Erstwhile, what's that
earthy smell about you?

29:37.040 --> 29:38.530
Is it perfume?

29:38.640 --> 29:40.608
I'm not wearing any perfume.

29:41.480 --> 29:44.165
Must be your essence.

29:44.520 --> 29:47.888
AMELIA: Colonel. Tremendous play.
I didn't see that one.

29:47.960 --> 29:49.200
No, no one ever does.

29:49.280 --> 29:51.123
It's my sneaky maneuver
I picked up in the Punjab.

29:51.280 --> 29:54.045
Oh! Exotic!

29:55.160 --> 30:00.121
My, Miss Charming, what
beauteous skin you possess.

30:01.600 --> 30:03.967
Reawy?

30:05.320 --> 30:08.483
Well, that's because late at
night when I'm all alone,

30:08.960 --> 30:11.042
I put my face in the fire.

30:12.960 --> 30:14.405
AMELIA: Really?
(MR. WATTLESBROOK SNORING)

30:15.200 --> 30:17.680
It's like a porcelain plate.

30:18.080 --> 30:20.924
ANDREWS:
It's like being in a kiln.

30:25.200 --> 30:26.929
(MUSIC PLAYING IN DISTANCE)

30:31.560 --> 30:33.289
(ROMANTIC MUSIC PLAYING)

30:34.440 --> 30:36.283
(MARTIN SINGING)

30:41.120 --> 30:46.809
<i>♪ Wake up and
suddenly you're in love ♪</i>

30:52.000 --> 30:53.331
(MUSIC STOPS)

30:56.920 --> 30:58.604
Sorry.
I didn't mean to bother you

30:58.760 --> 31:00.444
if you're in the
middle of something or...

31:00.720 --> 31:01.767
You are a little lost?

31:01.920 --> 31:02.967
No.

31:03.120 --> 31:05.885
I was just walking around, and
then I heard music and so...

31:06.120 --> 31:09.408
Quick. Get in before Wattlesbrook
confiscates this thing.

31:11.920 --> 31:13.445
Let's hope you're not her spy.

31:13.760 --> 31:15.808
Mrs. Wattlesbrook?
Yeah.

31:15.960 --> 31:19.043
She made me sign half a dozen
proper behavior agreements...

31:19.200 --> 31:20.486
Right.

31:20.560 --> 31:23.643
Swear to keep any modern contraption
out of sight of the guests.

31:23.760 --> 31:25.125
Right.

31:26.160 --> 31:27.889
Including you, Miss Erstwhile.

31:28.120 --> 31:31.090
I'm not a spy.
I swear.

31:31.360 --> 31:35.410
And you don't have to call me
Miss Erstwhile. It's Jane.

31:36.520 --> 31:38.045
Martin.

31:40.640 --> 31:42.483
I am so sorry
about this afternoon.

31:42.560 --> 31:45.564
No, no. Don't be.
Don't even worry about it.

31:45.680 --> 31:47.489
I would have
been absolutely fine

31:47.640 --> 31:49.483
if it weren't for
Prince Valiant showing up.

31:49.640 --> 31:50.926
The actors are
paid to be valiant.

31:51.000 --> 31:52.047
Right.

31:52.120 --> 31:56.808
They have some "Most Valiant
Player of the Month" award.

31:57.400 --> 32:00.643
Still, it's nice to have
a little break from them.

32:05.080 --> 32:07.321
Do you mind if I
turn back on your music?

32:07.680 --> 32:09.364
No, of course not.

32:13.240 --> 32:14.605
(POP MUSIC STARTS)

32:16.240 --> 32:19.369
You're a real easy
listening kinda guy, huh?

32:20.600 --> 32:22.602
Yeah. It relaxes me.

32:23.680 --> 32:26.570
Yeah. The easier...
The easier, the better.

32:28.520 --> 32:29.931
Here it comes.

32:30.120 --> 32:35.126
<i>♪ I used to think that
love was just a fairy tale ♪</i>

32:35.200 --> 32:37.362
You're a really great singer.

32:37.440 --> 32:40.649
You've got really
great taste in gowns.

32:40.720 --> 32:42.290
You make it
a little hard for me

32:42.360 --> 32:45.125
to take myself
seriously in this getup.

32:45.200 --> 32:48.124
Where are you in there?
There you are, yeah.

32:51.400 --> 32:53.050
Do you slow dance?

32:54.200 --> 32:55.281
Sure.

32:57.800 --> 33:04.160
<i>♪ Suddenly life has
new meaning to me ♪</i>

33:07.800 --> 33:11.168
I don't remember Wattlesbrook
teaching us that move.

33:12.000 --> 33:15.482
Yeah, neither will those
posh boys up at the house.

33:19.320 --> 33:20.765
(THUMPING)

33:21.080 --> 33:23.686
Ah. I almost forgot about it.

33:23.760 --> 33:27.287
Do you have another girl
hidden around here somewhere?

33:27.400 --> 33:28.481
Yeah.

33:29.600 --> 33:31.045
What was that?

33:31.120 --> 33:33.122
Shh.
You don't wanna scare her.

33:36.640 --> 33:37.880
(WHINNYING)

33:37.960 --> 33:39.530
Hey, hey, hey.

33:39.760 --> 33:41.091
(SHUSHING)

33:42.480 --> 33:44.084
Hey, hey, hey.

33:45.360 --> 33:48.125
Wow. You put
all the girls at ease?

33:48.560 --> 33:50.130
Only the wild ones.

33:54.520 --> 33:55.851
We almost missed it.

33:56.480 --> 33:58.721
Is this horse about to
have a baby right here?

33:59.520 --> 34:01.045
I've never seen
anything being born.

34:01.120 --> 34:02.326
Go get me some straw.
Wait a second.

34:02.400 --> 34:04.971
Are you gonna have to stick your hands
up in and flip it or something?

34:05.080 --> 34:06.525
Jane, just go get her some straw.
Yeah, all right.

34:06.760 --> 34:08.205
(HORSE WHINNYING)

34:09.080 --> 34:11.242
Breathe, you can do this.

34:11.360 --> 34:12.804
Straw. Get it.
Yeah.

34:13.639 --> 34:14.880
I found some!

34:14.960 --> 34:16.724
Okay. Thanks, Jane.

34:17.280 --> 34:18.645
My God, what's that?

34:19.520 --> 34:20.521
Jane.

34:20.639 --> 34:21.641
I'm coming right now.

34:21.719 --> 34:23.529
Get the straw, Jane!

34:24.159 --> 34:28.051
Push! Push! Push!

34:28.800 --> 34:30.245
That's it...

34:30.320 --> 34:32.083
Oh, my... Sparkle.

34:32.159 --> 34:33.241
I found it!

34:33.320 --> 34:35.004
Jane, it's beautiful.

34:35.080 --> 34:36.844
Got the straw.

34:36.920 --> 34:39.002
Oh, my gosh!

34:39.080 --> 34:41.128
It's the miracle of birth.

34:44.480 --> 34:46.847
There you go.
Up you get, buddy.

34:49.000 --> 34:51.161
Run free, little Sparkle.

34:56.000 --> 34:58.048
Prince Valiant
couldn't do that.

34:58.120 --> 34:59.451
No.

35:00.560 --> 35:03.848
That was amazing, though.
That was really amazing.

35:05.080 --> 35:07.686
I should probably get going.

35:08.960 --> 35:10.450
You got...

35:10.520 --> 35:12.284
Might not want that.
(LAUGHS)

35:15.320 --> 35:17.766
Can I give you something first?

35:18.880 --> 35:20.041
Just“

35:32.080 --> 35:34.845
Wanted to do that for a while.

35:34.920 --> 35:37.082
Good night, Jane Erstwhile.

35:37.160 --> 35:38.525
Good night.

35:48.400 --> 35:53.406
"She had had many a hint from Mr.
Knightley, and some from her own heart."

35:53.480 --> 35:55.403
I have one, too.

35:56.080 --> 35:57.445
Ooh.

35:58.040 --> 36:00.725
Mr. Darcy said to Jane,

36:01.560 --> 36:05.087
"Jane, listen.
Listen right now.

36:05.760 --> 36:08.491
"If you were to
sleep with me tonight,

36:08.600 --> 36:11.649
"I would actually
speak to you the next day,

36:12.640 --> 36:17.851
"unlike any man that you will
meet 100 years from now."

36:19.800 --> 36:21.768
(VOCALIZING)

36:22.760 --> 36:25.081
Please.
Please shut your hole.

36:27.280 --> 36:28.441
(CHUCKLES)

36:28.760 --> 36:32.287
Men and women wouldn't even
touch before marriage,

36:33.360 --> 36:36.364
let alone be alone in
the same room together.

36:37.120 --> 36:38.451
I don't think he would ever say

36:38.520 --> 36:41.649
something like that,
and he was a gentleman.

36:42.800 --> 36:44.290
(CLOCK CHIMING)

36:46.320 --> 36:48.288
MISS CHARMING:
Why are we sewing again?

36:49.440 --> 36:53.365
I guess this is how women must
have spent a lot of their time.

36:54.080 --> 36:58.768
Well, if the men don't
come back from hunting soon,

36:58.840 --> 37:00.968
I'm gonna ask for a refund.

37:03.240 --> 37:07.006
What about you, Miss Erstwhile?
Are you enjoying yourself?

37:07.080 --> 37:10.482
It is a shame we are
so awkwardly grouped.

37:10.560 --> 37:13.404
Two gentlemen and three ladies,

37:13.480 --> 37:17.326
leaving you always to
bring up the rear alone.

37:21.840 --> 37:23.649
If you'll excuse me,
I think I'm gonna

37:23.840 --> 37:25.683
go to the library
for a little while.

37:40.000 --> 37:41.764
Jane.
(SHUSHES)

37:41.920 --> 37:43.365
I'm reading.

37:48.760 --> 37:52.321
You're not really allowed to read
down on the sluice gate. Okay?

37:52.760 --> 37:55.161
You know, this is off-limits,
okay? This is...

37:55.240 --> 37:58.244
This is really very
dangerous down here. Okay?

37:58.800 --> 38:00.689
Anything could happen.

38:02.360 --> 38:04.886
I mean,
I don't have to be reading.

38:06.760 --> 38:07.761
I just...

38:08.760 --> 38:10.330
Martin, come on.

38:10.400 --> 38:13.449
I'll go crazy if I have to sit
up in that house all afternoon.

38:13.560 --> 38:14.891
You love it up there.

38:15.200 --> 38:17.009
All those guys
paid to adore you.

38:17.080 --> 38:20.050
Come on, check out the butler.
He's got a 14-pack.

38:21.040 --> 38:22.201
You're right,
I'm gonna go find him.

38:22.400 --> 38:23.526
Yeah?

38:38.600 --> 38:39.965
You win.

38:40.040 --> 38:41.644
<i>♪ Looking from
the window above</i>

38:41.720 --> 38:44.246
<i>♪ It's like a story of life</i>

38:45.080 --> 38:47.765
<i>♪ Can you hear me?</i>

38:48.120 --> 38:50.930
<i>♪ Came back only yesterday</i>

38:51.000 --> 38:53.526
<i>♪ Who went further away</i>

38:54.080 --> 38:56.890
<i>♪ Want you near me</i>

38:57.840 --> 39:01.208
<i>♪ All I needed was
the love you gave</i>

39:02.360 --> 39:05.762
<i>♪ All I needed for another day</i>

39:06.400 --> 39:09.244
<i>♪ And all I ever knew</i>

39:10.040 --> 39:11.644
<i>♪ Only you</i>

39:15.160 --> 39:18.209
<i>♪ Sometimes when
I think of her name</i>

39:18.280 --> 39:20.567
<i>♪ When it's only a game</i>

39:21.280 --> 39:23.965
<i>♪ And I need you</i>

39:24.440 --> 39:27.011
<i>♪ Listen to the words
that you say</i>

39:27.080 --> 39:29.811
<i>♪ It's getting harder to stay</i>

39:30.400 --> 39:33.244
<i>♪ When I see you ♪</i>

39:35.080 --> 39:36.889
MRS. WATTLESBROOK:
Martin, the birds.

39:36.960 --> 39:38.644
I'll see you later?

39:38.720 --> 39:43.328
Yeah. I just gotta put away a few fake
birds. Maybe see you at the stables?

39:44.120 --> 39:45.451
Okay.

39:54.200 --> 39:55.804
ANDREWS:
Awful as spread, is this one.

39:56.080 --> 39:58.367
But really. Never before...

40:00.040 --> 40:02.407
I'm gonna need a new
inkwell in my room.

40:02.480 --> 40:04.369
Are you?
Yeah, it's empty.

40:04.440 --> 40:05.521
Really?

40:05.600 --> 40:08.365
And what are you going to pen
while you're there?

40:08.440 --> 40:11.011
Maybe a little journal
of your time and experiences?

40:11.080 --> 40:13.731
Maybe the Declaration of Independence.
Really?

40:13.800 --> 40:15.325
Sumptuous beans.
My favorite.

40:15.400 --> 40:16.606
Yummy.

40:17.120 --> 40:18.610
How does one go about
eating a fish this big?

40:18.680 --> 40:19.681
They're so delicious!

40:20.160 --> 40:21.889
Baked, stewed.

40:21.960 --> 40:23.564
Refried.

40:23.640 --> 40:24.971
Marvelous.
(TAPPING GLASS)

40:26.160 --> 40:29.482
Everyone. I have great news.

40:30.120 --> 40:34.170
Captain George East has just
arrived from the West Indies.

40:41.520 --> 40:42.806
Good morning, ladies.

40:43.840 --> 40:45.490
You're beautiful.

40:47.320 --> 40:49.721
I hear you were
just made captain.

40:50.320 --> 40:52.084
Do tell us the story.

40:52.200 --> 40:54.282
Yes, we like stories. Please do.
Can't wait.

40:54.880 --> 40:58.407
I were raised on the sea. Ferrying
goods between the islands.

40:59.240 --> 41:03.006
But when Napoleon struck, I joined
arms with me British brothers.

41:04.120 --> 41:06.043
Bravi, bravi.

41:06.720 --> 41:10.167
Within months
I were first mate,

41:10.240 --> 41:12.686
and then came my
moment of destiny.

41:13.320 --> 41:16.210
Imagine one lone
British frigate,

41:16.280 --> 41:18.442
surrounded by four
French war crafts,

41:18.520 --> 41:19.646
cap'n dead on the deck.

41:19.720 --> 41:21.449
"Surrender," came the cry.
Anyone buying this?

41:21.880 --> 41:23.769
"Never," said I.

41:24.240 --> 41:25.651
Did you die?

41:27.560 --> 41:31.804
Now I were tempted to surrender,
but I had to hearten me men.

41:32.920 --> 41:34.570
"Death first."

41:37.440 --> 41:41.490
But surely there could be
no dishonor in surrender

41:41.600 --> 41:45.002
with your captain dead
and your men so outnumbered?

41:45.080 --> 41:48.163
When my seaman's heart
tell me what to do,

41:48.240 --> 41:50.846
I do not fear to
follow through.

41:51.400 --> 41:53.289
That rhymes. That rhymes.

41:53.360 --> 41:54.600
But right now,

41:56.760 --> 41:59.331
my seaman's heart
bid me do thusly.

42:01.760 --> 42:05.048
You are a most
sensual creature.

42:06.600 --> 42:07.567
Thank you.

42:07.640 --> 42:08.971
On. (CHUCKLES)

42:20.840 --> 42:22.649
(MUSIC PLAYING ON EARPHONES)

42:25.440 --> 42:27.807
ANDREWS: I say.
Steady on, Captain.

42:29.440 --> 42:30.965
This is absurd.

42:32.800 --> 42:33.881
Oh!
Oh!

42:34.800 --> 42:35.961
Watch out, Nobley.

42:36.040 --> 42:37.883
No, don't get up
too quickly, George.

42:37.960 --> 42:39.246
I believe the ladies are needed

42:39.320 --> 42:41.721
in the drawing room
with Mrs. Wattlesbrook.

42:41.800 --> 42:43.290
Lizzie darling.

42:43.440 --> 42:44.646
I'll be along shortly.

42:44.720 --> 42:46.722
I'm your humble servant,
My Lady.

42:46.800 --> 42:49.087
<i>MRS. WATTLESBROOK: Ladies,
please join me in the parlor</i>

42:49.160 --> 42:53.165
<i>for my lecture series
on bonnets, bosoms and vices.</i>

43:02.520 --> 43:04.045
Hi.
Hey.

43:06.720 --> 43:08.006
What do we have planned today?

43:08.240 --> 43:11.164
What, you couldn't find anyone
else to flirt with today?

43:12.400 --> 43:14.721
I saw you parading
around with those actors.

43:15.160 --> 43:17.367
I thought you
weren't into that stuff.

43:17.440 --> 43:18.680
Maybe I am.

43:19.560 --> 43:21.085
Well, I've never
really been able to

43:21.200 --> 43:22.565
respect the kind of
women that come here.

43:22.640 --> 43:25.530
So I guess I was fooling myself
that you weren't one of them.

43:26.080 --> 43:28.321
What, so are you
breaking up with me?

43:28.400 --> 43:30.050
Breaking up?

43:30.120 --> 43:32.487
I didn't realize
we were going steady.

43:32.560 --> 43:35.086
No, sorry, I didn't mean it.

43:52.320 --> 43:56.211
<i>WOMAN: (ON TV) If I was sane when I shot
you, I would have aimed for your head.</i>

43:57.160 --> 43:58.321
CAPTAIN EAST:
Did you see that?

43:58.880 --> 44:00.848
That was amazing, George.

44:00.920 --> 44:02.331
I mean,
really beautiful acting.

44:02.400 --> 44:03.845
CAPTAIN EAST: I had to
drink human breast milk

44:03.960 --> 44:05.530
supplements to get arms that big.
ANDREWS: Ugh!

44:05.600 --> 44:06.601
Mean...

44:08.040 --> 44:09.690
Must be what makes
your hair so shiny.

44:09.760 --> 44:11.125
Can I use your power socket?

44:11.560 --> 44:14.040
But you'll have to turn off the telly.
George, do you mind?

44:14.120 --> 44:15.167
Well, I...

44:15.240 --> 44:17.242
Well, we'll watch it later.
Okay.

44:18.400 --> 44:20.687
Welcome to the Pleasure Dome.

44:21.840 --> 44:23.604
Thank you.
MARTIN: Hey, George.

44:23.720 --> 44:24.801
Hey, Martin. You good?

44:24.880 --> 44:25.927
Yeah.

44:26.840 --> 44:28.649
Welcome back, eh.

44:29.280 --> 44:31.647
How are the ladies
treating you this year?

44:31.720 --> 44:34.007
Well, I can't complain.

44:34.080 --> 44:35.650
I can't complain.

44:35.720 --> 44:36.926
You really let yourself go.

44:38.160 --> 44:39.571
What? Really? What?

44:39.640 --> 44:41.608
Don't. Leave the boy alone.

44:41.680 --> 44:43.444
How is life in the stables?

44:44.080 --> 44:46.731
My horses are less
trouble than women.

44:50.120 --> 44:52.851
What do you guys
think of that girl, Jane?

44:52.960 --> 44:54.530
What's its name?
You know, Miss...

44:54.600 --> 44:55.931
Erstwhile.

44:56.000 --> 44:58.048
CAPTAIN EAST: Yeah, I could
slap that between a bun.

44:58.120 --> 45:00.202
Well, she's a bit peculiar.

45:00.280 --> 45:01.327
CAPTAIN EAST: She's hot.

45:01.440 --> 45:02.521
She's all right.

45:03.400 --> 45:04.561
(STEREO PLAYING)

45:04.680 --> 45:07.923
(AMELIA SINGING IN PITCHY VOICE)
<i>♪ No flower of her kindred</i>

45:08.000 --> 45:12.403
<i>♪ No rosebud is nigh</i>

45:12.520 --> 45:17.162
<i>♪ To reflect back her blushes</i>

45:17.240 --> 45:23.247
<i>♪ Give sigh for sigh ♪</i>

45:23.320 --> 45:24.560
(TAPE STOPS)

45:24.880 --> 45:27.326
MRS. WATTLESBROOK: Perfect,
Lady Heartwright. Perfect.

45:27.400 --> 45:29.687
I have no words to describe it.

45:30.360 --> 45:31.805
I say.

45:31.880 --> 45:35.566
I would die enraptured to hear
you play, Miss Erstwhile.

45:35.640 --> 45:37.165
No, not tonight, not tonight.

45:37.240 --> 45:38.730
Go on, go on.
Please.

45:38.800 --> 45:41.724
Miss Erstwhile, I insist.

45:42.320 --> 45:43.481
(PARTS)

45:45.600 --> 45:46.726
Okay.

45:48.320 --> 45:50.243
Allow me.
Thank you.

46:02.680 --> 46:04.921
I only really know one song.

46:05.000 --> 46:06.968
Play that one then.
Not surprising.

46:07.520 --> 46:09.409
So I'll just play that.

46:13.200 --> 46:16.568
(PLAYING <i>HOT IN HERE</i>)

46:22.640 --> 46:24.529
<i>♪ It's getting hot in here</i>

46:24.600 --> 46:26.807
<i>♪ So take off all your clothes</i>

46:26.880 --> 46:29.201
<i>♪ I am getting so hot</i>

46:29.280 --> 46:32.011
I'm gonna take my clothes off

46:32.080 --> 46:33.320
I never

46:38.040 --> 46:40.168
I think I will retire early.

46:44.640 --> 46:46.688
That was frigging awesome.

46:49.880 --> 46:51.723
(PIANO PLAYING)

46:55.720 --> 46:57.802
(AMELIA SINGING IN PITCHY VOICE)

47:15.600 --> 47:17.204
Where are you going?
(EXCLAIMS) Whoa!

47:17.280 --> 47:19.681
Sorry. Sorry.
I didn't know

47:19.760 --> 47:22.843
I became a ninja when
startled in a strange place.

47:22.920 --> 47:26.003
My father, if he were alive,
would die of shame.

47:26.080 --> 47:27.809
And here was I thinking
that any father would be

47:27.880 --> 47:30.247
delighted to have
a ninja as a daughter.

47:34.840 --> 47:36.604
(MARTIN SINGING IN DISTANCE)

47:38.120 --> 47:39.531
Excuse me.

47:40.480 --> 47:41.925
Miss Erstwhile.
Yes.

47:42.000 --> 47:44.401
I don't know if
you realize that

47:45.400 --> 47:49.485
it's not proper in this
particular time, or any time,

47:49.560 --> 47:52.086
for a lady to be
alone after dark...

47:53.120 --> 47:55.885
Okay. Let alone cavorting
with the servants...

47:55.960 --> 47:57.200
Cavort?

47:57.280 --> 47:58.566
When doing so might lead to...

47:58.640 --> 48:00.051
Did you just say "cavort"?

48:00.120 --> 48:02.248
There's just something about
that guy I really don't...

48:02.320 --> 48:04.721
Aren't you all righteous
concern, Mr. Nobley?

48:04.800 --> 48:08.009
Thank goodness you've saved me from
sullying myself with the help.

48:08.800 --> 48:10.689
Don't be so ridiculous.

48:11.160 --> 48:12.650
Insufferable.

48:16.160 --> 48:19.881
Well,
good evening, Miss Erstwhile.

48:20.800 --> 48:22.643
Good evening,
Mr. Wattlesbrook.

48:22.720 --> 48:27.169
Still awake, are you?
Up to some mischief, I hope.

48:28.120 --> 48:31.010
Just needed some fresh air.
If you'll excuse me.

48:31.320 --> 48:33.163
No, no, stay a moment.

48:33.720 --> 48:37.441
We might engage in
a private game of whist.

48:38.320 --> 48:39.606
That's a four-person game.

48:39.680 --> 48:41.205
We could be partners.

48:41.640 --> 48:45.531
Little wink-wink, little
nudge-nudge, under the table.

48:45.600 --> 48:47.204
I think I should go to bed now.

48:47.280 --> 48:48.850
Precisely my point.
No.

48:48.920 --> 48:51.287
This is so not
Regency appropriate!

48:51.360 --> 48:54.284
We can make it part of the game.
Do a little role play.

48:54.360 --> 48:56.806
Get off of me.
Get off of me!

48:58.360 --> 48:59.930
Miss Erstwhile?
(GROANING)

49:00.040 --> 49:01.690
Are you all right?

49:02.200 --> 49:05.329
Whatever is the matter? I didn't
have time to locate my breeches.

49:07.000 --> 49:08.684
Why, Mr. Wattlesbrook,
not again.

49:08.960 --> 49:10.689
Little slag attacked me!

49:11.040 --> 49:13.566
Well, obviously.
She is a ninja.

49:18.160 --> 49:19.446
Come here.

49:19.920 --> 49:21.763
I have to tell you,
the lads are not gonna

49:21.840 --> 49:23.251
cover up for you anymore.
I promise you.

49:23.320 --> 49:24.970
MR. WATTLESBROOK:
Just don't tell the missus!

49:25.040 --> 49:26.963
Well, I won't
tell the missus, but...

49:27.040 --> 49:28.087
MR. NOBLEY: I'll escort
you to your room.

49:28.200 --> 49:29.281
I'm okay now.

49:29.400 --> 49:31.084
Thank you. I just...

49:31.720 --> 49:35.247
As long as there aren't any other
Mr. Wattlesbrooks lurking around.

49:35.320 --> 49:37.084
I cannot give Andrews
a glowing reference,

49:37.200 --> 49:40.204
though I do believe
you could take him down.

49:40.280 --> 49:41.566
(CHUCKLES)

49:42.480 --> 49:46.804
Miss Erstwhile, are you sure there's
nothing more I can do for you?

49:46.920 --> 49:48.570
I'm fine.

49:50.160 --> 49:52.128
I should just go to bed.

49:53.960 --> 49:55.291
Good night.

49:59.640 --> 50:01.404
Apparently I bought
the cheap package.

50:01.480 --> 50:03.628
<i>MOLLY: The cheap package?
You kidding me?</i>

50:03.654 --> 50:04.190
No.

50:04.240 --> 50:05.730
I don't even think
my character gets

50:05.800 --> 50:07.564
the "happily ever
after" storyline.

50:07.640 --> 50:09.290
<i>I am going to kill
that travel agent.</i>

50:09.400 --> 50:11.641
I'm so mad I wasted
all my money.

50:11.720 --> 50:13.370
<i>Okay, enough is enough.</i>

50:13.440 --> 50:17.411
<i>You just need to come home
and buy your Tercel back.</i>

50:18.800 --> 50:22.009
Molly, I'm kind of
a mess, aren't I?

50:22.120 --> 50:23.281
<i>That's an understatement.</i>

50:23.360 --> 50:26.523
I wanna get over
all of this stuff,

50:26.600 --> 50:29.524
but if I leave now,
I'll always wonder "What if?"

50:29.600 --> 50:31.648
<i>So, what are you gonna do?</i>

50:36.080 --> 50:38.082
I'm going to take
charge of my story.

50:38.160 --> 50:40.527
An Austen heroine gets engaged
by the end of the book,

50:40.640 --> 50:42.210
so that is what
I'm going to do.

50:42.280 --> 50:44.089
Why don't you go
for Captain East?

50:44.600 --> 50:45.886
Look how hot he is.

50:45.960 --> 50:47.724
And he's a soap star.

50:47.800 --> 50:49.325
(GUN FIRING)

50:52.480 --> 50:53.970
Captain East?

50:55.320 --> 50:57.129
Okay. East it is.

50:57.480 --> 50:59.323
But can you help me, please?

50:59.400 --> 51:01.687
I mean, this is not gonna work.

51:03.560 --> 51:08.361
I've prepared my entire life
for this very moment.

51:10.320 --> 51:11.560
Someone's coming, hurry up.

51:18.880 --> 51:21.281
Heartwright had
millions of them.

51:21.840 --> 51:24.923
She's as dumb as a light post.
She'll never notice.

51:25.000 --> 51:26.411
Oh, my God.

51:26.520 --> 51:28.010
Look at this one.

51:28.960 --> 51:31.281
I love stealing
things from her.

51:32.920 --> 51:34.763
Watch my mouth.

51:34.840 --> 51:36.001
Blast.

51:37.440 --> 51:38.441
Blast.

51:38.560 --> 51:39.607
Good. Good.

51:40.480 --> 51:43.643
Bloody Americans.
(GRUNTS)

51:46.920 --> 51:50.208
Bloody Americans.
(GRUNTS)

51:51.560 --> 51:54.006
You got it.
You are the queen.

51:54.080 --> 51:55.286
Really?

51:56.680 --> 51:58.444
(POP SONG PLAYING)

52:10.480 --> 52:13.211
<i>♪ Her hair is Harlow gold</i>

52:14.640 --> 52:17.086
<i>♪ Her lips sweet surprise</i>

52:18.760 --> 52:21.366
<i>♪ Her hands are never cold</i>

52:22.640 --> 52:24.847
<i>♪ She's got Bette Davis eyes</i>

52:24.920 --> 52:27.571
<i>♪ She'll turn the music on you</i>

52:29.080 --> 52:31.731
<i>♪ You won't have
